<TEXT>
<P>
 RINGS, PLEASE: Charmaine Whalen was one wife too many. The Palmdale resident, 
24, became suspicious after husband Vernon Pierce failed to come meet her 
family after their April wedding, so she sent police to his Glendale, Ariz., 
home . . . where another of his four wives was knocking on his door.Now, 
ex-model Pierce, 29, is facing bigamy charges. Whalen (B7) won't be fooled 
again. She had dreamed of becoming a police officer. "Now I really want to do 
it." 
</P>
<P>
 PICTURE PERFECT: It's been a topsy-turvy year in the San Fernando Valley, and 
it's all reviewed on pages B2 and B3 today. . . . "Images of 1994" include The 
Times Valley Edition's most memorable photos, from the triumphs of a Little 
League championship team to rebuilding quake-wracked freeways. 
</P>
<P>
 HOLIDAZE: A break between Christmas and the New Year? Not if you observe 
Kwanzaa. The seven-day cultural celebration, which began Monday, draws 18 
million African descendants worldwide, including many participants in the 
Valley. Says Leslie Small, a Pan African studies professor at Cal State 
Northridge: "I think it's been catching on. There's this whole sense of 
cultural consciousness taking place among African Americans." Jeff Schnaufer 
</P>
