<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: CAMARILLO; POSTPONED AERIAL SPRAYING TO RESUME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF McDONALD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Aerial spraying of the pesticide malathion was rescheduled for Wednesday night 
after flights Tuesday were canceled by the Cooperative Medfly Project in 
Camarillo due to heavy fog. 
</P>
<P>
 Low-flying helicopters were expected to take off about 10 p.m. Wednesday as 
state agriculture officials continue their attack on the Mediterranean fruit 
fly, which was first found in Camarillo in late September. 
</P>
<P>
 Wednesday night's malathion spraying over 16 square miles in east Camarillo 
would be the sixth of 12 scheduled applications. 
</P>
<P>
 On Tuesday, dozens of people concerned about the long-term health effects of 
the aerial spraying protested against the chemical's use outside the Ventura 
County Health Department in Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
 State and local health officials maintain that the pesticide is safe in small 
doses. JEFF McDONALD 
</P>
