<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEIGHBORHOOD EATERY: FULL PLATES ON NEW YEAR'S EVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL KRIKORIAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 If you want to celebrate New Year's Eve without enduring the dumb snacks and 
drunken fools that mar so many parties, consider going to a restaurant. As 
usual, some of the top South Bay restaurants will be preparing special 
offerings for New Year's Eve.  
</P>
<P>
 At The Depot in Old Torrance, chef Michael Shafer is offering several specials 
for New Year's Eve. One is a barbecued New York steak ($19.95) basted with 
Shafer's own Thai sauce: rice vinegar, fresh ginger, garlic, cilantro, brown 
sugar, tomato paste and both sesame oil and sesame seeds. The steak is sliced 
and fanned out over a mound of shiitake, oyster and tree mushrooms, carrots and 
red bell peppers. 
</P>
<P>
 Peppered swordfish ($19.95) comes with hoppin' John, the traditional Southern 
New Year's Day stew of rice, black-eyed peas, vegetables and Creole seasonings. 
In the style of chef Daniel Boulud, who gained fame at his New York restaurant 
Le Cirque for serving a black sea bass with a red wine sauce, chef Shafer 
lavishes grilled albacore tuna ($17.95) with a red wine reduction heady with 
porcini mushrooms. The fish is accompanied with pecan corn bread dressing.  
</P>
<P>
 Over at the little Palette Cafe, nearly hidden in the shadow of the large 
Gable House bowling alley, chef Tom Kamijo will prepare a three-course dinner 
for $27.50. The meal begins with a choice of sauteed oysters in black bean 
sauce, shrimp cake in fennel cream, or a pate of venison, foie gras and 
truffles with apple chutney. Main course highlights include lobster, scallops 
and shiitake ravioli with a rich lobster sauce, or a roasted rack of lamb with 
Cabernet sauce and goat cheese mashed potatoes. For dessert, there's pumpkin 
pudding and a pear cake with assorted fresh fruits. 
</P>
<P>
 Now, I can't guarantee there won't be any drunken fools at either place, but 
the chances of getting a good meal are very good. And you can be safe at home 
in time to ring in the New Year. 
</P>
<P>
 The Depot is at 1250 Cabrillo St., Torrance, (310) 787-7501. Open Monday 
through Friday, 11:30 a.m. to 2:30 p.m. and Tuesday through Sunday, 5:30 to 11 
p.m.  
</P>
<P>
 The Palette Cafe is at 22549 Hawthorne Blvd., Torrance. (310) 373-7055. Open 
Tuesday through Saturday, 11:30 a.m. to 2:30 p.m., Tuesday through Sunday, 5:50 
to 9:30 p.m.  
</P>
<P>
 MICHAEL KRIKORIAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
